"""
mkt-context commentary — Proverbs chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-19-21.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS_CONTEXT = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>The comparison of the blameless poor man over the perverse-lipped rich man belongs to a recurring Proverbs pattern (see 28:6) that deliberately inverts the prosperity assumption embedded in much ANE wisdom: Egyptian Instructions presuppose that the wise man rises and prospers, but Proverbs insists that integrity outranks social advantage. The verse implies that speech is the index of character — <em>iqqēš śəpātāyw</em>, \"perverse in his lips,\" marks the opposite of the blameless walk regardless of wealth status.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The pairing of desire/soul without knowledge (<em>daʿat</em>) and haste in feet captures the ANE wisdom diagnosis that undisciplined eagerness is a form of ignorance. Hosea 4:6 — \"my people are destroyed for lack of knowledge\" — represents the prophetic version of the same indictment: uninstructed zeal drives Israel headlong into apostasy. The verse identifies <em>daʿat</em> as the regulative power that converts energetic desire into purposeful action; without it, speed is just faster error.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The observation that a man's folly ruins his way, then his heart rages against YHWH, is a compressed psychology of self-deception with canonical echoes. The pattern appears in Israel's wilderness narrative (Exod 14–17; Num 14): the people's own failures and distrust of divine provision repeatedly produce rage against Moses/YHWH rather than self-examination. Lamentations 3:39 asks the same question — \"why should a living man complain, a man, about the punishment of his sins?\" — as the corrective Proverbs implies.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The social observation that wealth attracts friends while poverty repels them reflects the economic sociology of the ancient Near East, where patron-client networks were the primary safety net. Job 19:13-19 provides the narrative illustration: Job's brothers, acquaintances, close friends, and household members all abandon him in his poverty/suffering. The Proverbs observations on wealth and friendship are descriptive of social reality, not endorsements — they form part of the wisdom tradition's unsentimental account of human social dynamics that prepares for the countercultural friendship ethics of ch17:17 and 18:24.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The false witness (<em>ʿēd šāqer</em>) who will not go unpunished appears three times in this chapter grouping (vv5, 9, 28) and echoes the ninth commandment of the Decalogue (Deut 5:20: \"you shall not give false testimony against your neighbor\"). Deuteronomy 19:16-21 prescribes lex talionis for false witnesses — the punishment they intended for their victim falls on them — which grounds the Proverbs declaration in covenant law. The repetition underscores that truthful speech is not merely a virtue but a covenant obligation with divine enforcement.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The generous man whom everyone seeks — <em>yəḥallû-pānê nādîb</em>, \"many curry favor with the noble/generous\" — reflects ANE patron-client dynamics where access to a generous benefactor was a survival strategy. The Wisdom of Ptahhotep counsels approaching the great man at the right time; Proverbs 19:6 observes this social reality without endorsing the flattery involved. The contrast implicit in the verse is between those who seek the generous man for what he gives and the friend who loves at all times (17:17).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The triple abandonment of the poor man — brothers hate, friends depart even further, he pursues with words but they are gone — echoes Job's social isolation (Job 19:13-19) and anticipates the NT's theology of the poor as those whom the world has rejected. The verse likely reflects the social reality of kinship-based economic systems where family networks were the first line of poverty relief; when even kin withdraw, the poor man is left without the covenant community's protective obligations (Lev 25; Deut 15:7-11).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Acquiring wisdom (<em>lēb</em>, heart) and guarding understanding (<em>bînāh</em>) as the path to loving one's own soul and finding good connects wisdom-acquisition to self-interest in the most basic sense: the person who gains wisdom gains life-flourishing. Deuteronomy 4:6 frames Israel's obedience to the statutes as the wisdom that demonstrates the nation's greatness to the nations — so that guarding divine instruction is simultaneously guarding the soul. The verb <em>šāmar</em> (guard/keep) links wisdom to the covenant-keeping posture of the whole Torah.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The repetition of the false witness saying from v5 with the slight variation — <em>yōʾbēd</em>, \"perishes\" — intensifies the consequence. The Deuteronomy 19:16-19 legal context makes explicit that the fate of the false witness is not merely social but covenantal and eschatological: YHWH himself is the ultimate witness against false testimony. The bracketing of vv5 and 9 around the social observations of vv6-8 keeps the judicial frame in view: these social dynamics operate within YHWH's moral governance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Luxury (<em>taʿănûg</em>) unsuitable for a fool parallels a servant ruling over princes — both are social disorders violating the wisdom concept of <em>ḥāmās</em>, fit order. The verse reflects ancient social hierarchies in which wisdom was understood to have a natural correspondence to role: the person who had not learned self-governance through wisdom was by definition unsuited for positions of power or enjoyment. The parallel appears implicitly in Qohelet 10:5-7 — the reversal of wisdom-order as a social evil seen under the sun.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Slow to anger and the glory of overlooking offenses connects to the royal virtue ideal prominent in Proverbs 16:32 and ANE royal inscriptions. Egyptian royal wisdom consistently presents the king as one who does not act in the heat of passion; the Aramaic Ahiqar sayings similarly praise the man who swallows his anger. Within the Proverbs framework, this virtue is not merely social grace but reflects the divine attribute — YHWH is <em>ʾerek ʾappayim</em>, slow to anger (Exod 34:6), and the person who embodies this becomes an image-bearer of the divine patience.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The king's wrath like a lion's roar and his favor like dew on grass draws on the ancient Near Eastern royal-lion iconography that appears in Assyrian, Babylonian, and Egyptian royal imagery. The lion was the symbol of royal power throughout the ancient world; Proverbs does not merely use the metaphor but applies it to both the threatening and the benevolent aspects of royal power. The dew metaphor (see also Ps 110:3; 2 Sam 17:12) captures the life-giving power of royal blessing in a rain-dependent agrarian economy.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The foolish son as father's ruin and the contentious wife like a constant dripping of rain reflects ancient household economics in which the family unit was both economic and social capital. The ANE household (<em>bêt ʾāb</em>) was the basic unit of survival; a son who dissipated family resources or a household relationship marked by incessant conflict threatened the entire structure. The same dripping-roof image appears in 27:15, and both verses presuppose that household harmony is not merely domestic preference but essential to wisdom's flourishing.</p>",
    "14": "<p>House and riches as inherited from fathers, but a prudent wife from YHWH, draws on the ANE wisdom tradition that recognized two kinds of goods: those acquired through normal social channels (inheritance, commerce) and those that transcend human arranging. Genesis 24 provides the canonical narrative illustration — Abraham's servant prays for YHWH to identify the right wife for Isaac, and Rebekah's appearance is explicitly framed as divine provision. The verse does not devalue inherited wealth but insists that the wisdom-quality of a spouse exceeds what human prudence alone can secure.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The connection between deep sleep (<em>tardēmāh</em>) and poverty uses the same vocabulary as the first deep sleep in Genesis 2:21 (Adam's sleep during Eve's creation) — but here it signals not creative rest but passive waste. The agricultural calendar of the ancient world left no margin for sloth: plowing, planting, harvest, and storage were time-bounded operations. Wisdom literature's recurring attack on laziness (6:6-11; 24:30-34; 26:13-16) reflects this agricultural reality, where the sluggard's inaction had communal as well as personal consequences.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Keeping a commandment to keep one's soul, and despising one's ways dying — the conditional structure ties covenant obedience to life-preservation in the Deuteronomic mode. Deuteronomy 8:1 — \"all the commandments I command you today you shall be careful to do, so that you may live\" — frames obedience as the path of life. Proverbs 19:16 applies this covenant logic individually: commandment-keeping is the existential alternative to life-contempt, and the one who treats his ways with contempt (NIV: \"who is contemptuous of his ways\") courts death.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Lending to YHWH by giving to the poor draws on the Deuteronomy 15:7-11 framework of poverty relief as covenant obligation. The legislation there frames generosity to the poor brother as an anticipation of the sabbatical year release; here Proverbs identifies such giving as a direct transaction with YHWH who will repay. The theological move — YHWH as the guarantor of loans to the poor — transforms charity from a social virtue into a covenantal transaction. Leviticus 25's jubilee theology provides the broader canonical frame: YHWH owns the land, its produce, and its people, so caring for the poor is stewardship within YHWH's economy.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The command to discipline your son while there is hope, and not set your heart on his death, reflects ANE pedagogical assumptions about the malleability of the young person before character becomes fixed. The Egyptian Instruction of Any warns against neglecting the formation of the young; the Babylonian wisdom texts similarly identify the formative years as the window of possibility. The ominous second half — \"do not set your heart on putting him to death\" — likely means \"do not spare rod to the point where he earns capital punishment\" (Deut 21:18-21 lists the rebellious son scenario).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The great-anger man (<em>gədal-ḥēmāh</em>) who must bear the penalty, and if you rescue him you will have to do it again, reflects the ANE wisdom observation that character formation happens early and that intervention without transformation produces dependency. The verse implies that rescuing the chronically angry person from consequences is not mercy but enabling — it perpetuates rather than resolves the problem. The social observation anticipates the NT distinction between consequences that lead to repentance (2 Cor 7:10) and consequences that are simply evaded.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Listening to counsel and accepting instruction as the path to wisdom in the end reflects the intergenerational wisdom-transmission pattern central to Proverbs 1-9. The phrase <em>bəʾaḥărîtekā</em>, \"in your end/future,\" echoes the temporal horizon of wisdom: short-term resistance to discipline produces long-term foolishness, while short-term submission produces long-term flourishing. The Egyptian wisdom texts from Amenemope and Ptahhotep begin precisely with this exhortation to receive instruction without resistance.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The sovereignty declaration — many plans in a man's heart, but YHWH's counsel (<em>ʿăṣat YHWH</em>) stands — forms a pair with 16:9 (\"a man plans his way, but YHWH directs his steps\") and 20:24 (\"a man's steps are from YHWH\"). The <em>ʿēṣāh</em> (counsel/plan) of YHWH appears in Isa 14:26-27 and 46:10 as the irresistible divine purpose that no human scheming can thwart. Proverbs places this not as a fatalistic curtailment of human planning but as the frame within which wisdom accepts both the planning and the divine overrule.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The desirability of loyal love (<em>ḥesed</em>) and the preference for the poor man over a liar connects the covenant virtue of <em>ḥesed</em> — God's own faithful covenant love (Exod 34:6-7) — to the horizontal ethics of the wisdom tradition. The term <em>ḥesed</em> in Proverbs carries the full covenantal weight it has in the Psalms and Hosea: it is the quality of loyal, steadfast, generous faithfulness that holds relationships together. The verse implies that <em>ḥesed</em> is a more reliable social bond than either wealth or status — the poor man with <em>ḥesed</em> outranks the prosperous liar.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The fear of YHWH leading to life, and abiding in satisfaction without evil visitation, connects the <em>yirʾat YHWH</em> theme of Proverbs 1:7 to the concrete outcome of flourishing (see also 14:27; 22:4). Deuteronomy 8:3 frames obedience to YHWH as the source of life — \"man does not live by bread alone, but by every word from the mouth of YHWH.\" The fear of YHWH in Proverbs is not mere religious feeling but the epistemic and moral orientation that shapes all of life; here its result is the <em>śābēaʿ</em> (satisfied/full) life protected from harm.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The sluggard who buries his hand in the dish and will not even bring it back to his mouth — the comic extreme of sloth — appears in nearly identical form in 26:15, suggesting it may be a proverbial stock image. The exaggeration is deliberate: the sluggard's paralysis is so complete that he cannot complete even the most basic act of self-preservation. ANE wisdom texts use hyperbole regularly to make a point unforgettable; the image fixes the endpoint of sloth more vividly than any sober description could.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The educational theory of Prov 19:25 — strike the scoffer and the simple learns, rebuke the discerning and he gains knowledge — reflects the ANE pedagogical observation that different learners respond to different signals. The <em>lēṣ</em> (scoffer) has placed himself beyond instruction; his punishment is not for his benefit but serves as an object lesson for the susceptible simple (<em>pětî</em>). This aligns with ancient legal practices in which public punishment had an explicitly deterrent function (Deut 13:11; 17:13; 21:21 all specify \"and all Israel shall hear and fear\").</p>",
    "26": "<p>Assaulting a father and driving out a mother — who brings shame and disgrace — directly echoes the fifth commandment's filial honor obligation (Exod 20:12; Deut 5:16) and the specific capital penalty for cursing parents (Exod 21:17; Lev 20:9). The household was the basic social and economic unit of the ancient world; the breach of parental authority was not merely a domestic problem but an attack on the social fabric and the covenant community's intergenerational transmission of wisdom and faith.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Stop listening to instruction and you will stray from words of knowledge — the warning frames wisdom-acquisition as an ongoing active discipline, not a one-time achievement. The Shema's command (Deut 6:4-9) frames Israel's relationship to the Torah as continuous hearing (<em>šəmaʿ</em>), learning, and teaching; the abandonment of hearing is the beginning of apostasy in the prophets (Isa 6:9-10; Jer 5:21; Hos 4:6). Proverbs 19:27 identifies the same dynamic at the individual level: the cessation of receptive learning is already the beginning of error.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The worthless witness mocks justice and the mouth of the wicked swallows iniquity — the courtroom metaphor is applied to the person whose speech itself is corrupt. The legal background of the covenant community (Deut 19:15-21) presupposes the witness as a crucial social institution; the person whose mouth is an iniquity-swallower has made himself a corrupting force in the judicial system on which the community's justice depends. The verb <em>yəballa'</em> (swallows) suggests not passive receipt but active consumption of wrongdoing.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Judgments prepared for scoffers and beatings for the backs of fools closes the chapter with the covenantal consequence framework: <em>šəpāṭîm</em> (judgments) are prepared — the passive form implying divine preparation — for those who have placed themselves beyond correction. The ANE wisdom tradition consistently identified the scoffer/mocker as the person who has made himself unteachable, a social toxin who corrupts those around him (see 22:10). The prepared judgments here correspond to the Deuteronomic curse list: systematic consequences built into the moral order for covenant contempt.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>Wine as mocker and strong drink as brawler, and being led astray by them as lack of wisdom, connects to multiple canonical frames. The Nazarite vow (Num 6:1-4) and the Levitical priestly abstinence from wine (Lev 10:9) indicate that wine impairs the judgment necessary for holy service. Genesis 9:20-23 provides the narrative archetype: Noah's wine-induced vulnerability produces a violation of family honor and a curse. Hosea 4:11 identifies wine and new wine as taking away the heart (<em>lēb</em>) — the same faculty Proverbs identifies as wisdom's seat.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The king's terror like a lion's growl — the same royal-lion image as 19:12 — functions within the ancient Near Eastern understanding of kingship as participation in cosmic order-maintenance. Assyrian royal iconography routinely depicted the king as a lion; lion hunts were a royal liturgy demonstrating the king's power to subdue chaos. Within Proverbs' theology, the king's wrath is a legitimate and terrifying reality, but it operates within YHWH's sovereignty (21:1; 16:10-15) — the lion-king is himself subject to the lion of YHWH's order.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Honor belonging to the man who keeps away from strife while every fool breaks out — the contention/peace contrast reflects the ANE ideal of the honorable man who resolves disputes rather than generates them. The Egyptian Instruction of Amenemope repeatedly counsels against the heated man (<em>ḥrr</em>) in contrast to the quiet man (<em>grw</em>); the quiet/peaceable man is the wisdom ideal in multiple wisdom traditions. Within Proverbs, strife is consistently associated with pride (13:10) and folly, while peace-seeking reflects the wisdom that belongs to the fear of YHWH.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The sluggard who does not plow in autumn and seeks at harvest but finds nothing maps onto the agricultural cycle of the ancient Levant, where autumn plowing (October-November) after the early rains was the essential preparation for the winter wheat and barley crops. Missing the plowing window meant no harvest — the biological and climatic consequence was irreversible within that year. The wisdom observation is both agricultural and moral: there are seasons of opportunity whose loss cannot be compensated by later effort, a principle that applies to wisdom-formation as much as farming.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The purpose in a man's heart as deep water and the man of understanding drawing it out reflects the ANE metaphor of wisdom as water from a deep well — see 18:4, where a man's words are deep waters and the fountain of wisdom a bubbling brook. The counselor/advisor role in ancient courts was precisely this drawing-out function: Solomon's wisdom (1 Kgs 3-4) is partly expressed in his ability to perceive and articulate what others could not reach. The verse implies that wisdom in others is not immediately visible but requires the intelligent questioner to bring it to the surface.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"Many a man proclaims his own steadfast love (<em>ḥesed</em>), but a faithful man who can find?\" — the rhetorical question about the rarity of reliable <em>ḥesed</em> appears in a cluster with Mic 7:2 (\"the godly has perished from the earth, and there is no one upright among mankind\") and Ps 12:1 (\"save, O LORD, for the godly one is gone\"). The gap between professed and practiced <em>ḥesed</em> is a recurring wisdom and prophetic observation. The verse functions as background for the NT's christological claim that YHWH's own <em>ḥesed</em> is incarnated in one who is reliably faithful where all humans fall short.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The righteous man walking in his integrity, with blessed children after him, echoes the Deuteronomic pattern of generational blessing for covenant faithfulness (Deut 7:9; Exod 20:5-6: \"showing steadfast love to thousands of those who love me and keep my commandments\"). Job 1:1 presents Job as walking in precisely this mode — blameless and upright — and the narrative tests whether Deuteronomic blessing is the inevitable correlate. The Proverbs observation is presented as wisdom's pattern, not a mechanical guarantee; it describes the characteristic trajectory of a life ordered around integrity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The king sitting on the judgment throne, winnowing all evil with his eyes, reflects the royal judicial function that was the primary obligation of ANE kings. The Code of Hammurabi prologue declares that the gods appointed Hammurabi to bring justice to the land and to destroy the wicked; 2 Samuel 15:2-4 shows Absalom exploiting the gap between royal judicial ideal and practice. Psalm 72 is the canonical royal ideal: the king who judges with righteousness and defends the cause of the poor. The Proverbs verse identifies the judicial discernment of the just king as a kind of cosmic ordering function.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"Who can say, I have made my heart clean; I am pure from my sin?\" — the rhetorical question expecting the answer \"no one\" represents Proverbs' most direct engagement with the universal sinfulness theme. 1 Kings 8:46 (Solomon's temple prayer: \"for there is no one who does not sin\") and Ecclesiastes 7:20 (\"there is not a righteous man on earth who does good and never sins\") are canonical parallels. The verse functions within Proverbs as a check on the book's own wisdom optimism: even the person who pursues wisdom cannot claim perfect heart-purity, which opens the question of what provision exists for the unavoidable moral deficit.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Diverse weights and diverse measures — both are abominations to YHWH — echoes the legislation of Leviticus 19:35-36 and Deuteronomy 25:13-16, which explicitly command just weights and measures as part of covenant ethics. Amos 8:5 indicts Israel for making the ephah small and the shekel great — commercial fraud using false measures as a specific form of covenant violation. The Proverbs abomination-language (<em>tôʿăbat YHWH</em>) is the strongest available condemnation, placing commercial dishonesty in the same category as idolatry — both are structural violations of the covenantal order.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Even a child is known by his deeds — the character-formation observation that behavior in the young reveals the trajectory of the adult reflects ANE pedagogical assumptions about the formative power of early habit. The Egyptian Instruction of Any warns: \"do not be a boy after another man's heart; what is told you, that will pass.\" Proverbs' emphasis throughout chapters 1-9 on catching the young person before habits are fixed presupposes this: the child's acts already indicate whether wisdom or folly is taking root.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The hearing ear and the seeing eye — YHWH has made them both — grounds the physical senses in their Creator in a way that makes their proper use an act of acknowledging divine provision. Psalm 94:9 makes the same argument from design: \"he who planted the ear, does he not hear? He who formed the eye, does he not see?\" The verse in Proverbs serves as a check on any presumption that human perception is autonomous: hearing and seeing are gifts that imply accountability for what one hears and sees.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Love not sleep, lest you come to poverty; open your eyes and you will have plenty of bread\" — the agricultural economy of the ancient Levant required consistent labor matched to seasonal rhythms. The planting and harvest windows were narrow; excessive sleep during critical periods was economically catastrophic. The verse's pairing of opened eyes with bread recalls the created order of Genesis 3:17-19, where bread comes through toil — the curse has redefined the relationship between labor and sustenance, and wisdom aligns with this creational reality rather than fighting it.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Bad, bad, says the buyer, then goes away and boasts\" — the commercial negotiation described here is a scene from ANE marketplace culture, where haggling was the normal mode of price-setting and the shrewd buyer's deprecation of goods was a standard tactic. The verse is descriptively amused rather than morally condemnatory: it observes the gap between the professed assessment and the private satisfaction as a wry comment on human nature in commerce. The observation sits alongside the verse about diverse weights (v10) as a two-part portrait of commercial ethics and practice.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"There is gold and abundance of costly stones, but the lips of knowledge are a precious jewel\" — the wisdom-as-treasure metaphor used here (see also 3:13-15; 8:10-11) grounds the comparison in the ANE luxury economy where gold and precious stones were the recognized stores of value. Proverbs 8:10-11 uses the same comparison. The verse elevates the <em>daʿat</em>-bearing speech above both metals and gems, which was a countercultural claim in a world where wealth was measured in exactly those commodities. The lips of knowledge are both rarer and more valuable than what the market recognizes as scarce.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"Take a man's garment when he has put up security for a stranger\" — the pledge/surety legislation appears in Exodus 22:26-27 (the creditor must return the poor man's cloak before nightfall, for it is his only covering) and Deuteronomy 24:10-13. Proverbs 20:16 (and 27:13) presents the commercial wisdom perspective: when someone guarantees a stranger's debt, the creditor is advised to take the garment immediately. The verse operates in the tension between legal protection of debtors (Exodus/Deuteronomy) and commercial prudence — wisdom literature's acknowledgment that ideals and social realities do not always align.</p>",
    "17": "<p>\"Bread gained by deceit is sweet to a man, but afterward his mouth will be full of gravel\" — the sweet-turning-to-gravel image recalls Proverbs 9:17 (\"stolen water is sweet, and bread eaten in secret is pleasant\"), the words of the Strange Woman whose guests end up in Sheol. The sweetness of illicit gain is a temporary sensory experience that is displaced by its true texture: worthless material that damages rather than nourishes. The Deuteronomic curse (Deut 28:33-34) involves laboring only to see the fruit consumed by enemies — the natural extension of the wisdom observation that deceptive prosperity reverses itself.</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"Plans are established by counsel, and by wise guidance wage war\" — the connection between wisdom-consultation and military success reflects the ANE practice of royal councils, where decisions of war were made after extensive consultation with advisors, diviners, and military commanders. Proverbs 15:22 and 24:6 elaborate the same principle. The war-counsel connection places wisdom in the domain of national survival, not merely personal flourishing — the stakes of ignoring counsel are civilizational. This aligns with the historical books' consistent narrative pattern: successful kings consult widely (Solomon; Hezekiah with Isaiah) while failed kings act unilaterally (Rehoboam; Ahab).</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"Whoever goes about slandering reveals secrets; therefore do not associate with a simple babbler\" — the warning against the gossip as a social danger reflects ANE counsel on friendship and trust. The Aramaic proverbs of Ahiqar contain similar warnings about the companion whose tongue cannot be trusted. Within the covenant community, the prohibition on tale-bearing appears in Leviticus 19:16 — \"you shall not go around as a slanderer among your people\" — placing the wisdom observation within a specific covenantal framework. The gossip who reveals secrets breaks the social fabric on which counsel and friendship depend.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"If one curses his father or his mother, his lamp will be put out in utter darkness\" — the extinguished-lamp metaphor for death draws on the ANE image of the lamp as the symbol of life, family continuity, and divine favor. The background legislation is Exodus 21:17 and Leviticus 20:9, both of which prescribe death for cursing parents. Proverbs converts the legal prescription into a wisdom metaphor: the lamp of the family line is extinguished when the foundational loyalty of filial honor is violated. The Psalms' royal promises (\"I have prepared a lamp for my anointed,\" Ps 132:17) use the same imagery in the positive register.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"An inheritance gained hastily in the beginning will not be blessed in the end\" — the connection between how wealth is obtained and its long-term outcome reflects the wisdom observation that process determines result in moral economics. The Ahab-Naboth narrative (1 Kgs 21) is the canonical illustration: hastily seized inheritance (Naboth's vineyard) becomes the site of Ahab's own death (1 Kgs 21:19). Proverbs consistently pairs the short-term appearance of gain with the long-term reversal: 10:2; 13:11; 21:6 all develop the theme that ill-gotten gains dissipate or curse.</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"Do not say, I will repay evil; wait for YHWH, and he will deliver you\" — the prohibition against personal vengeance draws on the Deuteronomy 32:35 declaration that vengeance belongs to YHWH: \"Vengeance is mine, and recompense, for the time when their foot shall slip.\" The wisdom instruction places the same prohibition in practical and theological context: waiting for YHWH to act is not passivity but faith in divine governance. The verse anticipates the apostolic teaching of Romans 12:17-21 (\"do not repay anyone evil for evil... leave it to the wrath of God\") which explicitly cites Deut 32:35.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The repeated abomination of diverse weights (v10, v23) — the bracketing of the chapter's commercial observations — reflects the structural seriousness of commercial integrity in the covenant community. The Holiness Code (Lev 19:35-36) places just weights alongside the prohibition on sorcery, idolatry, and oppression of the poor: all are violations of the covenant relationship with YHWH who \"brought you out of Egypt.\" The repetition within this chapter is a literary device of emphasis: commercial ethics are not peripheral but covenantal.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"A man's steps are from YHWH; how then can man understand his way?\" — the third of Proverbs' sovereign-steps sayings (16:9; 19:21; 20:24) approaches the paradox from a slightly different angle: not merely that YHWH directs what man plans, but that man cannot even fully comprehend his own path. The Jeremiah 10:23 parallel is direct — \"I know, O LORD, that the way of man is not in himself, that it is not in man who walks to direct his steps\" — and appears in a context of nations being subject to divine governance. Proverbs applies this cosmic principle to the individual life.</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"It is a snare to say rashly, 'It is holy,' and to reflect only after making vows\" — rash vows were a recognized legal and social problem in ancient Israel. Numbers 30 provides detailed legislation about the binding force of vows made by men, and Ecclesiastes 5:4-6 warns with similar urgency: \"when you vow a vow to God, do not delay paying it... it is better that you should not vow than that you should vow and not pay.\" The <em>môqēš</em> (snare) language implies that the rash dedication of something to YHWH without reflection ensnares the speaker in obligations they cannot fulfill — the piety itself becomes a trap.</p>",
    "26": "<p>\"A wise king winnows the wicked and drives the wheel over them\" — the threshing-wheel image for royal judgment connects to the agricultural processing of grain, where the winnowing fork and the threshing sledge separated wheat from chaff. Isaiah 28:27-28 uses threshing imagery for divine judgment on Israel. The wise king who winnows the wicked participates in the same cosmic sorting function: the royal court is the institutional site where YHWH's moral order is enforced. Psalm 72's portrait of the just king who crushes the oppressor (v4) develops the same royal-justice theme.</p>",
    "27": "<p>\"The spirit of man is the lamp of YHWH, searching all his innermost parts\" — the identification of the human spirit (<em>nišmat ʾādām</em>) as a divine lamp for self-examination connects to the creation of humanity in Genesis 2:7 where YHWH breathes the breath of life (<em>nišmat ḥayyîm</em>) into the human. The breath/spirit by which man lives is also the faculty by which he is knowable to YHWH from within. Job 32:8 makes a related claim: \"it is the spirit in man, the breath of the Almighty, that makes him understand.\" The lamp metaphor suggests that conscience is not autonomous human insight but a divine illumination from within.</p>",
    "28": "<p>\"Steadfast love and faithfulness (<em>ḥesed we-ʾěmet</em>) preserve the king, and by steadfast love his throne is upheld\" — the pairing of <em>ḥesed</em> and <em>ʾěmet</em> (faithfulness/truth) echoes the divine self-description in Exodus 34:6 and appears in the royal psalm tradition. Psalm 101 is the canonical royal <em>ḥesed</em> commitment — the king's vow to govern with integrity. The Proverbs verse places the king's reliance on these covenant virtues not merely as political strategy but as the theological condition of royal legitimacy: the throne that does not embody divine <em>ḥesed</em> is inherently unstable.</p>",
    "29": "<p>\"The glory of young men is their strength, and the splendor of old men is their gray hair\" — the honor given to each life stage reflects the ANE cultural pattern of assigning distinctive virtues to different phases of life. Egyptian wisdom literature assigns the vigor of youth and the wisdom of age as complementary goods. Within Israel, the elder system presupposed the accumulation of wisdom with years (Lev 19:32: \"you shall stand up before the gray head and honor the face of an old man\"). Proverbs presents the life stages as a complementary social ecology, not a competition.</p>",
    "30": "<p>\"Blows that wound cleanse away evil; strokes make clean the innermost parts\" — the painful-discipline-as-cleansing metaphor connects to the Hebrews 12:11 reflection on divine chastisement: \"for the moment all discipline seems painful rather than pleasant, but later it yields the peaceful fruit of righteousness.\" Proverbs 20:30 grounds this in the observation that external discipline can reach into the interior of character in ways that persuasion alone cannot. The verse acknowledges that transformation sometimes requires painful intervention — a counter-cultural claim against the ancient as well as modern preference for painless formation.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>\"The king's heart is a stream of water in the hand of YHWH; he turns it wherever he will\" — the irrigation-channel metaphor reflects the ANE hydraulic landscape where water management was a primary royal responsibility. Canals, channels, and irrigation systems were literally state infrastructure; the king who controlled water controlled life. The verse asserts that YHWH's governance of the king operates at the same level of total control — channeling rather than forcing, directing through the existing landscape. Isaiah 44:28-45:1's portrait of Cyrus as YHWH's shepherd and anointed, whom YHWH \"takes by the right hand,\" provides the canonical illustration of divine redirection of a non-Israelite king for covenant purposes.</p>",
    "2": "<p>\"Every way of a man is right in his own eyes, but YHWH weighs the heart\" — the divine heart-weighing image appears in the Egyptian Book of the Dead's judgment scene, where the heart is weighed against the feather of Ma'at, though the Proverbs usage is thoroughly Yahwistic. The parallel in 16:2 is nearly identical; together they form a consistent Proverbs teaching that self-assessment is structurally unreliable. Jeremiah 17:9-10 provides the prophetic parallel: the heart is deceitful above all things, and YHWH searches the heart. The Proverbs framework does not develop the doctrine of sin's depth as extensively as Jeremiah, but points toward the same reality.</p>",
    "3": "<p>\"To do righteousness and justice is more acceptable to YHWH than sacrifice\" — this verse is one of Proverbs' most direct engagements with the prophetic critique of sacrificial formalism. 1 Samuel 15:22 (\"to obey is better than sacrifice\"), Amos 5:21-24 (\"I hate, I despise your feasts\"), Isaiah 1:11-17 (\"what to me is the multitude of your sacrifices?\"), Hosea 6:6 (\"I desire steadfast love and not sacrifice\") — all belong to the same canonical tradition. Proverbs 21:3 shows that this priority is not merely prophetic protest but wisdom's own insight: justice and righteousness are not alternatives to worship but its presupposition and substance.</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"Haughty eyes and a proud heart, the lamp of the wicked, are sin\" — the trio of haughty eyes, proud heart, and lamp (symbol of life/prosperity) identifies the entire life-orientation of the proud person as sinful. Haughty eyes appear in the six-seven abominations list of 6:16-17 as the first item; Isaiah 2:11-12 announces YHWH's eschatological humiliation of all that is lifted up. The <em>nêr rəšāʿîm</em> (lamp of the wicked) echoes 13:9 and 24:20, where the wicked's lamp is put out — the flourishing that pride produces is temporary and ends in darkness.</p>",
    "5": "<p>\"The plans of the diligent lead surely to abundance, but everyone who is hasty comes only to poverty\" — the diligent/hasty contrast appears within the broader Proverbs pattern of time-sensitive wisdom. The Hebrew <em>ḥārûṣ</em> (diligent) shares a root with <em>ḥāraṣ</em> (to cut/sharpen), suggesting that diligence involves a kind of precision and intentionality rather than mere busyness. ANE agricultural wisdom consistently identified careful planning across seasons as the foundation of economic stability; the hasty person who skips preparation in the search for immediate return mirrors the sluggard in reverse — both fail through mismanagement of time.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"The getting of treasures by a lying tongue is a fleeting vapor and a snare of death\" — the <em>hebel</em> (vapor/breath/vanity) vocabulary links Proverbs to Ecclesiastes' governing metaphor for transient and futile things (Eccl 1:2). The pairing with \"snare of death\" grounds the vanity claim in a specific mechanism: the lying tongue that generates wealth also lays a death-trap for the one who uses it. Isaiah 28:15-18 presents a parallel: those who have made a covenant with death and falsehood their shelter will find that shelter swept away. Proverbs 21:6 anticipates the eschatological dimension that Ecclesiastes develops.</p>",
    "7": "<p>\"The violence of the wicked will sweep them away, because they refuse to do justice\" — the sweeping/dragging imagery (<em>gôrûrēm</em>) suggests the wicked being carried away by the very force of their own violence, like a flood carrying its source downstream. The prophetic judgment oracles use similar imagery: Amos 4-5 describes Israel being swept away by the very disasters they refused to turn from. The refusal to do justice (<em>mišpāṭ</em>) identifies the specific covenant failure: not ignorance but willful rejection of the community's legal and moral obligations.</p>",
    "8": "<p>\"The way of the guilty is crooked, but the conduct of the pure is upright\" — the two-path framework running through Proverbs (esp. chs 4-7) takes on a forensic coloring here: <em>hāpakpak</em> (crooked/tortuous) describes the guilty man's way, the winding evasive path of someone trying to avoid detection. The Egyptian Instruction of Amenemope uses the \"straight road\" and the \"crooked road\" as moral metaphors throughout; in Proverbs the framework is explicitly Yahwistic and connected to the legal/judicial metaphor of guilt and innocence.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"It is better to live in a corner of the housetop than in a house shared with a quarrelsome wife\" — the housetop-corner image belongs to a cluster of Proverbs sayings about household peace and contentious relationships (19:13; 25:24; 27:15). The flat-roofed house of ancient Israel and the wider ANE meant that the roof was genuinely usable living space — retreating there was a real option, not merely a rhetorical device. The verse does not condemn the woman but identifies a household dynamic that wisdom literature consistently treats as corrosive to the shalom that the household is meant to embody.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"The soul of the wicked desires evil; his neighbor finds no mercy in his eyes\" — the identification of evil desire as the defining characteristic of the wicked moves the diagnostic inward, to the level of appetite and orientation rather than merely behavior. The prophetic tradition makes the same diagnosis: Micah 2:1-2 describes those who devise wickedness on their beds because it is in the power of their hand — desire that shapes intention that produces action. Proverbs 21:10 is wisdom's shorthand for what the Sermon on the Mount will expand: wickedness is an orientation of the heart before it becomes an act.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"When a scoffer is punished, the simple becomes wise; when a wise man is instructed, he gains knowledge\" — the pedagogical observation that different learners respond to different teaching methods reflects the ANE wisdom tradition's practical sociology of education (see also 19:25). The punishment of the scoffer serves an instructional function for observers even when it fails to reform the scoffer himself; the teachable person needs only instruction. Deuteronomy's stipulation of public punishment as a deterrent (Deut 13:11; 17:13) institutionalizes the first dynamic; the rabbinic and wisdom traditions developed the second.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"The Righteous One observes the house of the wicked; he throws the wicked down to ruin\" — the capitalization of <em>maśkîl</em> as a divine subject (\"the Righteous One\") is contested, but the verse fits the Proverbs pattern of divine surveillance of household moral economies. YHWH's eye watching the righteous and wicked (Prov 15:3; Ps 11:4-7) frames the observation. The wicked household is not merely self-destructing but being actively subverted by divine governance — the wisdom observation and the prophetic announcement converge here.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Whoever closes his ear to the cry of the poor will himself cry out and not be answered\" — the lex talionis logic here is applied to social obligations: the person who refuses to hear the poor man's cry becomes a person whose own cry is refused. Deuteronomy 15:7-11 frames the care for the poor brother as a covenant obligation with divine enforcement; Leviticus 19:9-10 and 23:22 institutionalize gleaning rights for the poor. James 2:13 provides the NT development: \"judgment is without mercy to one who has shown no mercy.\" The Proverbs observation is not just social description but covenantal cause-and-effect.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"A gift in secret averts anger, and a concealed bribe, strong wrath\" — Proverbs' pragmatic acknowledgment of the gift/bribe economy reflects the ANE commercial and judicial culture where gifts to officials were a normal part of transaction and relationship management. The observation is descriptive rather than prescriptive: it does not commend bribery but acknowledges its practical effectiveness in managing interpersonal conflict. The same wisdom tradition elsewhere clearly prohibits bribery in judicial contexts (17:23; Exod 23:8; Deut 16:19) — the two observations together constitute wisdom's realistic and ethical engagement with economic practice.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"When justice is done, it is a joy to the righteous but terror to evildoers\" — the asymmetry of responses to justice (<em>mišpāṭ</em>) reflects the covenant community's two-track experience of divine judgment. The same act of justice is celebration and rescue for the righteous (Ps 97:8: \"Zion hears and is glad\") and catastrophe for the wicked (Ps 97:3: \"fire goes before him and burns up his adversaries\"). Micah 6:8's summary of covenant obligation — \"do justice, love kindness, walk humbly with your God\" — places justice as the first and most visible marker of covenant fidelity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"One who wanders from the way of understanding will rest in the assembly of the dead\" — the two-path structure of Proverbs (from ch4) reaches its eschatological endpoint: the wanderer from wisdom's path ends in <em>qəhal rəpāʾîm</em>, the company of the dead. The <em>rəpāʾîm</em> (shades/dead) in the Hebrew underworld tradition appear in Isaiah 14:9-10 as the previous inhabitants of Sheol mocking the fallen king of Babylon. Proverbs uses the Sheol destination not primarily as threat but as the natural terminus of the path that has wandered from understanding — the destination reveals where the path was always going.</p>",
    "17": "<p>\"Whoever loves pleasure will be a poor man; he who loves wine and oil will not be rich\" — the love-of-pleasure-leads-to-poverty observation connects to the canonical pattern of Deuteronomy 32:15 where Jeshurun (Israel) grows fat and kicks — abundance produces the abandonment of YHWH. Ecclesiastes 2:1-11 runs the full experiment of pleasure-seeking and reports the same conclusion: \"behold, all was vanity and a striving after wind\" (v11). The Proverbs observation is not asceticism for its own sake but the wisdom insight that pleasure as a primary goal systematically undermines the conditions of its own pursuit.</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"The wicked is a ransom for the righteous, and the traitor for the upright\" — the substitution language (<em>kōper</em>, ransom/atonement payment) applied to the wicked as a ransom for the righteous is difficult and debated, but it may reflect the observation that the wicked bear the consequences of disorder that would otherwise have fallen on the righteous. Isaiah 43:3-4 uses similar language of nations being given as ransom for Israel. The verse stands within the wisdom tradition's observation that moral order has a substitutionary logic — consequences find their proper recipients eventually.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"It is better to live in a desert land than with a quarrelsome and fretful woman\" — the desert-dwelling image (like the housetop corner of v9) reflects the cultural reality that the household was the center of economic, social, and family life in ancient Israel. The desert was the antithesis of civilization and provision; the fact that the desert is preferable to a contentious household indicates the severity of the damage that household conflict does to the <em>shalom</em> that wisdom cultivates. Ruth 1:1 and the wilderness narratives frame the desert as the place of testing and absence — the household's inverse.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"Precious treasure and oil are in a wise man's dwelling, but a foolish man devours it\" — the Joseph narrative (Gen 41-47) provides the canonical illustration of wisdom's storage-and-provision pattern: Joseph's wise management of Pharaoh's grain stores created abundance that survived seven years of famine, while those without such wisdom exhausted their resources immediately. Ecclesiastes 7:12 identifies wisdom as a shelter like money, but superior — \"wisdom preserves the life of him who has it.\" The contrast between wise preservation and foolish consumption is both economic observation and character diagnosis.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"Whoever pursues righteousness and kindness (<em>ḥesed</em>) will find life, righteousness, and honor\" — the pursuit of righteousness and <em>ḥesed</em> as the path to life positions these covenant virtues as the practical conditions of flourishing. Amos 5:4-6 frames the same pair as a matter of life and death: \"seek me and live... seek good, and not evil, that you may live.\" Micah 6:8 identifies exactly this combination — justice and <em>ḥesed</em> — as the summary of covenant obligation. The verb <em>rādap</em> (pursue/chase) suggests an active, sustained orientation rather than passive compliance.</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"A wise man scales the city of the mighty and brings down the stronghold in which they trust\" — the city-of-the-mighty motif may allude to the small-city parable of Ecclesiastes 9:14-15, where a poor wise man by his wisdom delivers the city besieged by a great king, though he is then forgotten. The Proverbs verse is more triumphalist: wisdom as a weapon that overcomes fortified strength. The David-Goliath narrative and the Gideon story (Judg 7) represent canonical illustrations of the principle that wisdom and divine favor overcome numerical and structural advantage.</p>",
    "23": "<p>\"Whoever keeps his mouth and his tongue keeps himself out of trouble\" — the connection between speech-discipline and self-preservation is a recurring Proverbs theme (12:13; 13:3; 18:21) with canonical roots in Psalm 34:13 (\"keep your tongue from evil and your lips from speaking deceit\") and James 3's extended reflection on the tongue's destructive power. The verse belongs to the wisdom tradition's consistent observation that speech is the primary moral arena: the person who has mastered the tongue has mastered the most volatile domain of daily life.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"'Scoffer' is the name of the arrogant, haughty man who acts with arrogant pride\" — the identification of the scoffer (<em>lēṣ</em>) as constitutively defined by arrogance (<em>zādôn</em>) and pride (<em>yāhîr</em>) connects to the broader Proverbs portrait of the scoffer as the endpoint of the foolishness spectrum. The scoffer is not merely ignorant but actively contemptuous of wisdom and its teachers (9:7-8; 13:1; 15:12). Isaiah 28:14-22 addresses the \"scoffers who rule this people in Jerusalem\" as those who have made a covenant with death — arrogance taken to its theological extreme.</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"The desire of the sluggard kills him, for his hands refuse to labor\" — the paradox of the sluggard destroyed by his own desires (desire for food, comfort, security) that his refusal to work ensures he cannot meet appears in 13:4: \"the soul of the sluggard craves and gets nothing.\" The Proverbs portrait of the sluggard is not merely about laziness but about a particular form of self-destruction through the gap between desire and effort. The ant passage of 6:6-11 presents the counter-image: the creature with no one commanding it provides for its own future through constant labor aligned with seasonal rhythms.</p>",
    "26": "<p>\"All day long he craves and craves, but the righteous gives and does not hold back\" — the contrast between the desire-without-satisfaction of the wicked/sluggard and the liberality of the righteous maps onto the Deuteronomic generosity principle. Deuteronomy 15:10 — \"you shall give to him freely, and your heart shall not be grudging when you give to him\" — commands the open-handed generosity that Proverbs 21:26 describes as characteristic of the righteous person. The righteous person's giving is not merely financial virtue but the overflow of a character oriented outward rather than inward.</p>",
    "27": "<p>\"The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination; how much more when he brings it with evil intent\" — the prophetic-wisdom convergence of 21:3 is deepened here: not only is justice preferable to sacrifice, but the sacrifice of the wicked actively offends YHWH. Isaiah 1:11-15 develops this at length: YHWH cannot endure the assemblies of those whose hands are full of blood. The \"how much more\" intensifier indicates that the problem is not merely the external performance of sacrifice but the intentionality behind it — evil intent makes an already problematic sacrifice into something categorically worse.</p>",
    "28": "<p>\"A false witness will perish, but the word of a man who hears will endure\" — the endurance of the reliable witness's word versus the destruction of the false witness connects to Deuteronomy 19:16-21's lex talionis for false testimony: what the false witness intended for his victim comes back on him. The contrast between the perishing false word and the enduring true word anticipates the NT's identification of the Logos (John 1:1-14) as the ultimate true word that endures — all false speech is temporary, while true speech participates in the enduring nature of divine truth.</p>",
    "29": "<p>\"A wicked man puts on a bold face, but the upright gives thought to his ways\" — the bold/brazen face of the wicked (<em>ʿāzaz pānāyw</em>) reflects the ANE and biblical image of shamelessness as a sign of moral degradation. Jeremiah 3:3 uses the same image for Israel's apostasy: \"you have the forehead of a prostitute; you refuse to be ashamed.\" The upright man's practice of examining his ways (<em>yābîn darkô</em>) is the practical wisdom discipline — the regular self-examination that keeps the path straight. The contrast is between the brazen refusal of self-examination and the careful attention to one's own trajectory.</p>",
    "30": "<p>\"No wisdom, no understanding, no counsel can avail against YHWH\" — the threefold negation of all human wisdom against divine governance echoes Isaiah 40:13-14's rhetorical questions about YHWH's incomparability: \"who has measured the Spirit of the LORD, or what man shows him his counsel?\" Job 38-41's divine speeches make the same case at length: no human wisdom comprehends or resists divine governance. Proverbs 21:30 places this not as a rebuke to wisdom but as its proper frame: all genuine wisdom operates within and defers to divine sovereignty rather than opposing it.</p>",
    "31": "<p>\"The horse is made ready for the day of battle, but the victory belongs to YHWH\" — the war-horse was the primary symbol of military power in the ancient Near East; the Egyptian and Assyrian armies were built around chariot forces, and possession of horses signified military capability. Psalm 33:17 — \"the war horse is a false hope for salvation, and by its great might it cannot rescue\" — is the canonical parallel. 2 Chronicles 20:15 provides the narrative instance: \"the battle is not yours but God's.\" Proverbs 21:31 does not forbid military preparation but insists that the confidence placed in it is misplaced — the prepared horse is appropriate; the misplaced trust is the problem.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in PROVERBS_CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'proverbs mkt-context: wrote {total} verses for ch 19–21')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
